d in relation to ideas about fiction, journalism, drama, poetry, the New Woman, gothic, horror and the Victorian sage.Key FeaturesDetailed readings of key texts provide models of how to read criticallyDemonstrates the interaction between genres to help think through modes of artistic experimentation and innovation in the periodExamines Neo-Victorian fiction, a popular genre todayStudent resources include electronic and reference sources, further reading and an extensive glossary of key critical terms and historical issues  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismx19th century. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074862562840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074863108740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748631087423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748631087/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK